        Should I Sell My Property Off-Market in Brisbane?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Off-market is not automatically better or worse than a full public campaign. Whether it suits your situation depends on your property, your agent's buyer network, and what you are trying to achieve.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a Brisbane real estate agent suggests selling off-market, the conversation often stalls at the surface level. Sellers hear "privacy" and "exclusivity" and either agree immediately or push back instinctively. What is worth doing instead is asking a more specific question: given my property, my situation, and the current state of the buyer market in my suburb, would limiting public exposure produce a better or worse result than a full campaign? The answer is almost never obvious, and a good agent should be able to walk you through the logic rather than simply advocating for one approach.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How agents actually find buyers for off-market properties</h2>
      <p>An off-market sale does not mean no marketing. It means marketing to a private audience rather than the general public. In practice, an agent with a genuine off-market capability will have a database of pre-qualified buyers who have registered interest in specific suburbs and property types, often after losing in previous competitive campaigns. These buyers are serious, have finance pre-approved in many cases, and are primed to act quickly when the right property becomes available.</p>

      <p>Beyond the database, agents identify off-market buyers through direct outreach to people who have attended recent open homes on comparable properties, buyer's agent networks (buyer's agents often know of pre-qualified buyers whose brief matches a specific property), and private referrals through the agent's professional and personal network in the suburb. A well-connected agent operating in the inner east can often name specific people who would buy a given property before they have even viewed it.</p>

      <p>The distinction that matters is between an agent who has a deep, current buyer database built through years of activity in your suburb, and one whose off-market process amounts to calling two or three contacts before putting it online. The first can generate real buyer competition in an off-market environment. The second cannot.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which Brisbane properties suit off-market</h2>
      <p>Not all properties suit an off-market approach equally. In Brisbane's inner east, the ones that tend to perform well off-market share certain characteristics. The property has a clear, specific buyer profile: families who want a particular street or school catchment, downsizers who want a low-maintenance freestanding home in a specific suburb, or investors who want a certain yield and configuration. When the buyer profile is specific and the agent knows who those buyers are, a targeted approach can match the outcomes of a broader campaign.</p>

      <p>Tightly-held streets with limited stock tend to have the strongest off-market potential. If comparable properties in the street rarely come to market, the agent is likely already fielding inquiries from buyers who have been waiting for years. A renovated Queenslander on a quiet Balmoral street, a large family home within the Cannon Hill Anglican College catchment, a waterfront Hawthorne property: in each case, there is a defined buyer cohort that has been actively watching the market and will move quickly when something suitable becomes available.</p>

      <p>Properties where the buyer pool is broad, shallow, or uncertain are harder to serve well off-market. A unit in a large complex, a property with unconventional features, or a home that needs significant work typically benefits from maximum exposure to find the one buyer in a large market who will pay a premium for what it offers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should ask before agreeing</h2>
      <p>Before agreeing to an off-market sale, ask your agent to be specific about four things. First, how many buyers in their current database match your property's profile? Not a rough number, but an honest estimate of how many people have registered interest in your suburb, your property type, and your approximate price point, and have done so in the last six to twelve months. Old database records that have not been recently contacted or updated are not useful indicators of genuine demand.</p>

      <p>Second, how will they create buyer competition in an off-market environment? A genuine off-market process involves multiple buyers being presented with the property simultaneously or in rapid succession, with each knowing others may be interested. Presenting to one buyer at a time without competitive tension is not a strategic off-market process, it is a private sale to a single party, which rarely produces the best price for the seller.</p>

      <p>Third, what price do they believe a full public campaign would achieve, and what comparable sales evidence supports that estimate? If the agent cannot give you a credible answer to this question, they cannot give you a credible answer to whether off-market is the right choice. The off-market vs full campaign decision is fundamentally a trade-off question: you are giving up some degree of market exposure (and potentially some degree of price tension) in exchange for speed, privacy, or reduced disruption. You need to know what you are giving up before you can decide whether the trade-off is worth it.</p>

      <p>Fourth, what is the fallback position if an off-market result is not achieved? A defined timeline for the off-market period, after which the property transitions to a full public campaign, protects you from an extended period of private marketing that fails to produce a result and then requires a public launch that carries the stigma of an already-stale property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How off-market pricing compares to the open market</h2>
      <p>The honest answer is that the price differential between off-market and publicly marketed sales in Brisbane's inner east is hard to quantify precisely because the sample sizes for direct comparisons are small. What the data consistently shows across comparable inner-east markets is that properties sold through full public campaigns in competitive conditions, with multiple registered bidders at auction or multiple written offers in a private treaty campaign, tend to outperform comparable off-market sales at the same period in the cycle.</p>

      <p>The exception is when the off-market sale occurs in a market environment where buyer confidence is very high and the agent has specific, motivated buyers who know comparable values. In those circumstances, an off-market sale to a ready buyer can match what a campaign would have achieved, net of marketing costs and the time and disruption involved. But this combination is the exception, not the rule.</p>

      <p>A reasonable frame for thinking about the pricing trade-off: marketing costs for a well-run Brisbane inner-east campaign typically range from $4,000 to $12,000 depending on property type and campaign scope. The incremental price benefit of a full public campaign over a private sale in a normally functioning market is generally larger than that. If an agent suggests going off-market, the burden of proof should be on them to demonstrate why the off-market approach is expected to close the gap to what the open market would produce.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to insist on a full public campaign</h2>
      <p>If your property has any of the following characteristics, a full public campaign is almost certainly the better choice. The property is unusual, aspirational, or hard to categorise: large blocks, houses with commercial zoning potential, architecturally significant homes, or properties with features that appeal to a narrow but international buyer base all need maximum exposure to find the right buyer. Off-market limits you to whoever the local agent happens to know, which may not include the buyer who would pay the most.</p>

      <p>If you have time to run a proper campaign and are not in a hurry, the financial case for full public marketing is strong. If the property has been sitting on the market for a while, off-market is unlikely to solve the problem: the issue is typically price or presentation, not exposure, and an off-market relisting after a failed campaign rarely generates better buyer confidence.</p>

